686
00:44:54.441 --> 00:44:56.693
Don't it say something about going
after what makes you happy?

687
00:44:56.860 --> 00:44:59.612
No, that's "the pursuit of happiness."
But what's your point?

688
00:44:59.780 --> 00:45:03.074
My point is I'm pursuing something,
and nobody looks too happy about it.

689
00:45:03.367 --> 00:45:05.743
But we're just looking out
for your interests.

690
00:45:05.911 --> 00:45:09.580
I appreciate that, but maybe you're
looking out for your interests more.

691
00:45:09.748 --> 00:45:13.084
You shouldn't ask people
to come here and pay
the freight on something.

692
00:45:13.252 --> 00:45:16.421
They pay, it still ain't good enough.
You think that's right?

693
00:45:16.588 --> 00:45:19.841
Maybe you're doing your job,
but why you gotta stop me
from doing mine?

694
00:45:20.384 --> 00:45:24.262
If you're willing to go through
all the battling to get where
you want to get,

695
00:45:24.430 --> 00:45:26.139
who's got the right to stop you?

696
00:45:26.306 --> 00:45:29.767
Maybe you got something you never
finished, something you wanna do.

697
00:45:29.935 --> 00:45:32.145
Something you never said
to somebody, something!

698
00:45:32.312 --> 00:45:34.480
And you're told no,
even after you pay your dues.

699
00:45:34.648 --> 00:45:37.233
Who's got the right
to tell you that? Who? Nobody!

700
00:45:37.401 --> 00:45:40.570
It's your right to listen to your gut.
It's nobody's right to say no

701
00:45:40.738 --> 00:45:44.157
after you earn the right to
be what you wanna be or
do what you wanna do!

702
00:45:46.160 --> 00:45:48.202
[♪♪♪]

703
00:45:48.370 --> 00:45:52.498
The older I get, the more things
I gotta leave behind. That's life.

704
00:45:52.666 --> 00:45:57.211
The only thing I'm asking you guys
to leave on the table is what's right.

705
00:46:14.646 --> 00:46:16.439
Yo! Have you seen
the paper today?

706
00:46:16.607 --> 00:46:18.733
Front row. Front row.

707
00:46:19.067 --> 00:46:21.152
MAN:
That is so great.

708
00:46:21.361 --> 00:46:23.863
All right, all right.
Let's go get some food. Food.

709
00:46:24.031 --> 00:46:27.867
Let's get a beer. Come on.
Come on.

710
00:46:28.327 --> 00:46:30.369
The last two pay-per-views
were in the toilet.

711
00:46:30.537 --> 00:46:33.164
You're not making
heavyweight-championship money.

712
00:46:33.332 --> 00:46:35.291
There's a bunch of nobodies
out there, Mase.

713
00:46:35.459 --> 00:46:38.503
I wanna talk to you about an
opportunity we should run with.

714
00:46:38.670 --> 00:46:42.507
Look at me. You heard Rocky Balboa
applied for a license and got one?

715
00:46:42.674 --> 00:46:44.550
I heard. Forget about him.
Hear me out. Hear me out.

716
00:46:44.718 --> 00:46:48.095
You want me to fight a guy I can beat
with both hands tied behind my back.

717
00:46:48.263 --> 00:46:51.641
Everybody knows you
could beat him sitting down.
That's not what it's about.

718
00:46:51.809 --> 00:46:55.061
It's about making money. We gotta
capitalize on that computer fight.

719
00:46:55.229 --> 00:46:57.980
This could do a million buys.
That's 1 5, 20 million to you.

720
00:46:58.148 --> 00:47:00.149
Forget about it.
No one's beating the door down

721
00:47:00.317 --> 00:47:02.985
to watch you fight anymore.
We got guaranteed fights.

722
00:47:03.153 --> 00:47:06.113
You wanna do this now in front
of your friends, we'll do it now.

723
00:47:06.281 --> 00:47:09.742
We got nothing. All the pay-per-view
fights you come up with got rejected.

724
00:47:09.910 --> 00:47:13.454
You know why? They're all bums
out there. Nobody cares about them.

725
00:47:13.872 --> 00:47:17.583
There's no marquee value.
But this Balboa thing is interesting.

726
00:47:17.918 --> 00:47:19.460
I don't wanna do it.
Listen to me.

727
00:47:19.628 --> 00:47:21.420
It's a has-been,
never-gonna-be world.

728
00:47:21.588 --> 00:47:23.548
Call it nostalgia,
whatever you want,

729
00:47:23.715 --> 00:47:26.926
but people relate to that stuff.
This is a no-lose. It's all good.

730
00:47:27.386 --> 00:47:29.971
Good for who?
For you! Not for me! For you!

731
00:47:30.305 --> 00:47:33.266
Maybe you don't understand.
People don't like you no more.

732
00:47:33.433 --> 00:47:36.894
They don't follow you.
They're not supporting you
anymore. Understand?

733
00:47:37.062 --> 00:47:39.188
Don't look at me like
I'm messing with your legacy.

734
00:47:39.356 --> 00:47:41.107
Every jock now thinks
they got a legacy.

735
00:47:41.275 --> 00:47:44.193
A legacy is what you get instead
of getting paid. That's a legacy.

736
00:47:44.361 --> 00:47:46.946
Don't talk to me like I'm stupid.
I'm not. I'm not no more.

737
00:47:47.114 --> 00:47:50.658
LOU:
Everybody knows you could kick
this old man's ass. But you don't.

738
00:47:50.826 --> 00:47:52.869
You leave him with a little
bit of dignity, so they say:

739
00:47:53.036 --> 00:47:56.539
"Mason Dixon's got compassion.
He's a decent guy, he's a nice guy."

740
00:47:56.707 --> 00:47:59.125
You get a whole new audience,
we'll double your money.

741
00:47:59.293 --> 00:48:01.335
You want a new image?
That's how you get it.

742
00:48:01.503 --> 00:48:03.254
To replace the one
that you two made?

743
00:48:03.422 --> 00:48:06.257
Whoa, wait. We made your
world green. You made the rest.

744
00:48:06.425 --> 00:48:08.384
All this is you.
You made all this junk happen.

745
00:48:08.552 --> 00:48:10.261
I've had it up to here
with this mess.

746
00:48:10.429 --> 00:48:12.930
Time for me to make changes.
I'm going to Martin's gym.

747
00:48:13.098 --> 00:48:14.807
We'll talk about it.
Forget this crap.

748
00:48:14.975 --> 00:48:17.351
I want Martin back.
There's nothing to talk about.

749
00:48:22.733 --> 00:48:24.817
[TRAIN HORN BLARING]

750
00:48:28.071 --> 00:48:29.822
How you doing?
Hey, what a surprise.

751
00:48:29.990 --> 00:48:32.408
I was driving around
the neighborhood, I thought,

752
00:48:32.576 --> 00:48:35.202
why not drive by and say hello?
You wanna come inside?

753
00:48:35.370 --> 00:48:38.414
No, the dog needs some exercise.
You wanna take a little walk?

754
00:48:38.582 --> 00:48:41.000
Yeah, yeah. All right.
It's nice outside.

755
00:48:41.168 --> 00:48:43.711
All right.
Nice and brisk.

756
00:48:43.879 --> 00:48:45.087
When did you
get a dog?

757
00:48:45.255 --> 00:48:47.340
We picked up Punchy
a couple of days back.

758
00:48:47.507 --> 00:48:48.716
Punchy?
Yeah.

759
00:48:48.884 --> 00:48:50.134
You named your
dog Punchy?

760
00:48:50.302 --> 00:48:52.011
Your kid come up
with the name.

761
00:48:52.179 --> 00:48:54.597
Oh, yeah? I think
that's disrespectful.

762
00:48:54.765 --> 00:48:56.515
Oh, no, no.
It's fine, really.

763
00:48:56.683 --> 00:49:00.019
No, it's easy to remember
and it's all that, you know.

764
00:49:00.187 --> 00:49:03.189
Listen, what do you think about
coming over to the restaurant?

765
00:49:03.357 --> 00:49:06.359
What for?
Well, you know, for, like...

766
00:49:06.526 --> 00:49:09.987
For work. The hostess is gonna
be having a kid. You'd do good.

767
00:49:10.155 --> 00:49:12.698
I don't know.
I'm telling you, you'd do so good.

768
00:49:12.866 --> 00:49:15.326
I appreciate what you're doing
for my kid, but I can't.

769
00:49:15.494 --> 00:49:17.954
Hey, listen, I think
you'd like it a lot.

770
00:49:18.121 --> 00:49:20.539
It's a nice environment,
it's very pleasant.

771
00:49:20.707 --> 00:49:22.792
Yeah, can we drop it?

772
00:49:25.253 --> 00:49:26.754
What's bothering you?

773
00:49:26.922 --> 00:49:29.173
Nothing. It's all right.
Listen, I gotta get back.

774
00:49:30.592 --> 00:49:32.551
No, it ain't all right.
Oh, come on.

775
00:49:32.886 --> 00:49:34.720
What?
I'm gonna be the first person

776
00:49:34.888 --> 00:49:37.348
people see when they walk in?
You give out menus.

777
00:49:37.516 --> 00:49:40.267
You say, "Hello, how are you?"
You sit people down.

778
00:49:40.435 --> 00:49:42.728
Look, if I can do it,
anybody can do it.

779
00:49:42.896 --> 00:49:46.148
You could find 1 0 better people,
a hundred better people for this job.

780
00:49:46.316 --> 00:49:48.150
Give it a try, like two weeks.

781
00:49:48.318 --> 00:49:50.111
I don't wanna try.

782
00:49:50.278 --> 00:49:52.530
Who put this stuff in your head?
Nobody.

783
00:49:52.698 --> 00:49:54.699
Well, it just don't
get in there by itself.

784
00:49:58.245 --> 00:50:00.204
Thanks for coming by.

785
00:50:00.539 --> 00:50:01.914
[♪♪♪]

786
00:50:02.082 --> 00:50:06.585
Yo, when was the last time you
went dancing? Has it been a while?

787
00:50:06.753 --> 00:50:08.629
Why are you asking?
I'm asking because

788
00:50:08.797 --> 00:50:12.091
you dance around these problems,
you might as well dance with me.

789
00:50:12.259 --> 00:50:15.261
I ain't that good, but I'm
better than the average bear.

790
00:50:15.429 --> 00:50:18.097
Where that came from,
I don't know.

791
00:50:18.765 --> 00:50:20.224
You're crazy.
Yeah, a little bit.

792
00:50:20.392 --> 00:50:23.644
But the way you're thinking
and talking, it's a little crazy too.

793
00:50:24.521 --> 00:50:28.149
Come on, you deserve better.
Really. Come on over.

794
00:50:28.316 --> 00:50:32.570
I need you to class my
place up. Philly needs you.

795
00:50:32.946 --> 00:50:36.615
And if you say, "Screw you, creepo"
again, I totally understand.

796
00:50:36.783 --> 00:50:39.201
But I'm warning you,
I'm gonna put myself,

797
00:50:39.369 --> 00:50:41.245
like, geographically in the
middle of the street here

798
00:50:41.413 --> 00:50:44.331
and stand here, me and Punchy,
and wave to the first bus, say:

799
00:50:44.499 --> 00:50:46.250
"Come on over here
and mash me!

800
00:50:46.418 --> 00:50:48.878
Little Marie turned down
the job at the restaurant.

801
00:50:49.046 --> 00:50:50.755
She thinks she's better than us."

802
00:50:50.922 --> 00:50:54.175
Oh, yeah? Well, there hasn't been
a bus down here in 20 years.

803
00:50:54.801 --> 00:50:56.802
Yeah?
No.

804
00:50:58.055 --> 00:51:00.514
Phew! That was a close call.

805
00:51:01.600 --> 00:51:06.604
Listen, seriously.
Come on over. It'd be nice.

806
00:51:09.232 --> 00:51:10.649
All right.

807
00:51:28.919 --> 00:51:30.503
MAN:
Paulie!

808
00:51:33.840 --> 00:51:35.633
Sorry, Paulie.

809
00:51:37.010 --> 00:51:38.719
Sorry.

810
00:51:38.887 --> 00:51:41.263
[♪♪♪]

811
00:52:10.001 --> 00:52:13.129
How are you?
Get my unusual up there.

812
00:52:13.296 --> 00:52:16.048
Excuse me.
Deliveries are in the back.

813
00:52:16.216 --> 00:52:17.925
I'm not a delivery guy.

814
00:52:18.093 --> 00:52:19.885
Well, do you have
a reservation?

815
00:52:20.053 --> 00:52:22.388
Do I look like a freaking Indian?

816
00:52:22.556 --> 00:52:24.223
[LAUGHING]

817
00:52:25.767 --> 00:52:28.060
Hey, Rock? Rocky?

818
00:52:32.983 --> 00:52:35.734
I think we've got a little bit
of a problem with this guy.

819
00:52:35.902 --> 00:52:38.237
Problem?
No, no, he's just a relative.

820
00:52:38.405 --> 00:52:40.698
Oh, okay.

821
00:52:43.243 --> 00:52:44.660
Yo, Paulie.

822
00:52:46.913 --> 00:52:48.914
What happened to your eye?
I hit it.

823
00:52:49.249 --> 00:52:51.041
Why?
Needed to.

824
00:52:51.668 --> 00:52:53.002
What happened?

825
00:52:53.170 --> 00:52:55.921
I'm celebrating, Rock.
Why?

826
00:52:56.089 --> 00:52:58.507
I retired.
Retired?

827
00:52:58.925 --> 00:53:01.051
[LAUGHING]

828
00:53:04.347 --> 00:53:06.932
So when did they start
giving retired people meat

829
00:53:07.100 --> 00:53:09.268
instead of watches, Paulie?

830
00:53:12.105 --> 00:53:14.064
I don't need a watch.

831
00:53:15.901 --> 00:53:19.278
I got a watch!
You gave me a watch!

832
00:53:19.487 --> 00:53:20.779
Paulie--

833
00:53:20.947 --> 00:53:23.449
I don't need no
goddamn watch.

834
00:53:25.118 --> 00:53:28.245
Yo, Paulie.
I got a watch!

835
00:53:29.539 --> 00:53:31.540
I got two watches!

836
00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.168
Yo, Paulie!

837
00:53:34.336 --> 00:53:36.670
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

838
00:53:40.926 --> 00:53:43.427
[♪♪♪]

839
00:53:46.514 --> 00:53:47.556
Yo, Paulie.

840
00:53:49.184 --> 00:53:50.684
Rock.

841
00:53:50.977 --> 00:53:55.397
It takes guts climbing back
in that ring, knowing you're
gonna take a beating.

842
00:53:58.109 --> 00:53:59.985
You're gonna do
all right, Rocko.

843
00:54:00.278 --> 00:54:01.612
How do you know that?

844
00:54:03.490 --> 00:54:06.075
The stuff
in the basement.

845
00:54:17.045 --> 00:54:18.796
Thanks, Paulie.

846
00:54:23.593 --> 00:54:26.512
Hey.
Hey, how you doing, Rock?

847
00:54:27.847 --> 00:54:30.015
You okay?
Yeah, good. How are you?

848
00:54:30.183 --> 00:54:31.809
Yeah, fine. This is great.
Good.

849
00:54:31.977 --> 00:54:34.645
Listen, some guys over there
wanna talk to you.

850
00:54:34.813 --> 00:54:37.606
Okay. You got it.
Okay?

851
00:54:41.027 --> 00:54:42.611
Thanks for coming by.
I appreciate it.

852
00:54:42.779 --> 00:54:43.779
Our pleasure.

853
00:54:43.947 --> 00:54:45.906
Wanna hear some stories?
LOU: What kind of stories?

854
00:54:46.116 --> 00:54:48.826
Well, a lot of people like to
hear these old fight stories.

855
00:54:48.994 --> 00:54:50.452
LOU: Maybe later.
Okay.

856
00:54:50.620 --> 00:54:55.082
I'm Lou DiBella. This is L.C. Luco.
He's Mason Dixon's manager.

857
00:54:55.292 --> 00:54:57.710
Will you sit down and join us?
Sure.

858
00:54:59.254 --> 00:55:02.047
You know, we have the promotional
contract for Mason Dixon,

859
00:55:02.215 --> 00:55:03.757
who's a big fan, by the way.
Really?

860
00:55:03.925 --> 00:55:06.051
When he heard you were
interested in fighting again,

861
00:55:06.219 --> 00:55:08.470
he thought why not try
to work something out?

862
00:55:08.638 --> 00:55:11.682
Like a special event.
Like a first-class exhibition fight.

863
00:55:13.226 --> 00:55:15.311
Why me?
He respects the hell out of you.

864
00:55:15.478 --> 00:55:19.440
All right? And let's be honest,
that computer fight got people
curious.

865
00:55:19.607 --> 00:55:20.816
This could be
very interesting.

866
00:55:20.984 --> 00:55:24.361
Yeah, but I ain't interested
in getting, like, mangled
and embarrassed.

867
00:55:24.529 --> 00:55:26.697
No, that's not gonna happen.
Never happen. No.

868
00:55:26.865 --> 00:55:31.035
Truthfully, I was thinking
more on a, like,

869
00:55:31.411 --> 00:55:35.039
minuscule, small level. You know.
Small fights, not big fights.

870
00:55:35.290 --> 00:55:39.251
Small fights. Things that--
Local. You know what I mean?

871
00:55:39.419 --> 00:55:42.921
Not a bad idea. Don't think
of it as big. Think of it like
an exhibition.

872
00:55:43.089 --> 00:55:46.675
Think of it as a glorified sparring
session. Here's something you'll like.

873
00:55:46.843 --> 00:55:49.386
We're gonna donate a portion
of the gate to charity.

874
00:55:49.554 --> 00:55:50.763
Well, that's always nice.

875
00:55:50.930 --> 00:55:53.265
It's good to give.
Yeah.

876
00:55:53.725 --> 00:55:55.309
Where's it taking place?

877
00:55:55.477 --> 00:55:56.852
Las Vegas.
Las Vegas.

878
00:55:57.020 --> 00:56:00.272
Nice and warm.
This cold's gotta be killing you.

879
00:56:00.440 --> 00:56:02.816
Little stiff.
You move better when you're warmer.

880
00:56:03.443 --> 00:56:05.069
Yeah.
And if nothing else,

881
00:56:05.236 --> 00:56:07.321
you'll have new stories to tell.

882
00:56:07.614 --> 00:56:10.449
I really gotta think about this.
LOU: Absolutely.

883
00:56:10.617 --> 00:56:11.617
Is that okay?

884
00:56:11.785 --> 00:56:12.993
I understand. No problem.
No problem.

885
00:56:13.370 --> 00:56:15.579
I'm gonna go over there.
You can order something.

886
00:56:15.747 --> 00:56:17.831
What do you recommend?
It's all edible.

887
00:56:18.041 --> 00:56:20.125
[LAUGHING]

888
00:56:20.752 --> 00:56:23.337
Okay. Thanks.

889
00:56:23.963 --> 00:56:27.800
We got him. Imagine if Dixon
met this bastard in his prime?

890
00:56:27.967 --> 00:56:30.427
He'd kill him. Kill him.
You ain't kidding.

891
00:56:30.970 --> 00:56:33.305
Man, I'm confused.

892
00:56:40.522 --> 00:56:42.439
ROCKY: I didn't think this
was gonna come along.

893
00:56:42.607 --> 00:56:44.233
MARIE:
But this is what you wanted, right?

894
00:56:44.401 --> 00:56:46.693
I don't know.
You know, I talk and I talk.

895
00:56:46.861 --> 00:56:48.987
Sometimes I think
what I'm saying is true,

896
00:56:49.155 --> 00:56:53.492
and then I look at myself and I'm
not even sure what is true anymore.

897
00:56:53.660 --> 00:56:56.662
Because it's like, I pushed
this crazy idea about fighting.

898
00:56:56.830 --> 00:56:58.372
I mean, what's it all about?

899
00:56:58.540 --> 00:57:01.500
Do I really care about standing
toe to toe and all that stuff,

900
00:57:01.668 --> 00:57:05.254
or, like my kid says,
is it just, like, ego?

901
00:57:05.422 --> 00:57:09.174
Or am I this old pug
who's just trying to replace
old pain with new pain?

902
00:57:09.342 --> 00:57:11.969
I don't know. I don't know.

903
00:57:13.721 --> 00:57:16.515
Look, I know
I usually don't say a lot.

904
00:57:16.683 --> 00:57:20.727
I'm always listening and looking.

905
00:57:20.895 --> 00:57:25.858
But who you are, the part
of you that's so full of life,

906
00:57:26.025 --> 00:57:28.068
we all have that feeling,
that fire,

907
00:57:28.236 --> 00:57:32.739
but usually never get a chance
to use it. And then it just goes away.

908
00:57:32.907 --> 00:57:37.870
But you can. You've got this
opportunity, so do it. Why not?

909
00:57:38.037 --> 00:57:42.332
I mean, this is who you are.
This is who you'll always be.

910
00:57:42.500 --> 00:57:45.794
And you don't move
aside for nobody until
you're ready to move.

911
00:57:45.962 --> 00:57:48.755
And it doesn't matter
how this looks to other people.

912
00:57:48.923 --> 00:57:51.216
All that matters
is how it looks to you.

913
00:57:51.426 --> 00:57:53.218
[♪♪♪]

914
00:57:53.386 --> 00:57:54.928
Rocky.

915
00:57:56.139 --> 00:57:58.140
Rocky, look at me.

916
